HERE_DOC EXAMPLES

simple example:

cat << EOF
hello
	world
EOF
what does this do?
every test in between the first EOF and the second EOF will be
passed to cat over its stdin, which reads from stdin and writes to
stdout

cat << "EOF"
hello $USER, $SHLVL is 1
EOF
here we do not perform expansions, everything from EOF until EOF
keeps it literal fo erm

echo 'foo' << EOF
bar
EOF
result of this is:
foo
what is actually happenning?
<< eof starts a here-document, so everything until eof is fed to
the commands stdin, so we basically say "send bar\n to stdin"

echo foo does not read from stdin at all, echo always prints its
arguments, so echo simply ignores stdin and prints foo

lesson:
a here-document only matters if the command actually reads from stdin
so everytime a command that doesnt not read from its used with heredoc
whatever is written between delimeters, gets ignored, however, if both commands
read from stdin, heredoc wins

echo foo | cat << eof
bar
eod

results in : bar

EXPANSIONS

-EOF yes, variables are expanded

<< eof
$USER, becomes milija-h

-'EOF'/"EOF" no, literal value is expanded

<< 'eof'/"eof"
$USER, stays $USER

to put it more simply, the delimiter is what determines wether expansions
happen or not, so if DELIMITER is not quoted is expands everything
because quotes are just literal characters that wrap the expanded
value, important, quotes are then mantained, with the expanded value

